This actually belongs in TOOTH1; the final /a/ is an independent morpheme (the 'argumentative' or 'nominal' marker /-a/), /s/ is the normal reflex of syllable-initial /j/, and /o/ is the normal reflex of PTG */ã/, i.e., PTG */hãj-a/ > Tocantins Asurini /hosa/.--SM

There is an interesting problem here: Tocantins Asurini has two words, /e-miat/ 'food; game' and /misat/, /misar-a/ 'deer'. Now, looking at the other words here, /e-miat/ is a better candidate for cognacy (especially if the /e-/ is, as I think it is, an independent morpheme marking alienable possession). But /misat/ is not a bad candidate either, and an /s/ is the normal development in Asurini of a PTG */j/ (*/mijat/ > /misat/ would be regular); and */mijat/ looks so close to /miat/ that I wonder if we don't have a case here in which a single PTG morpheme 'game, (meat) food)' split into two, /miat/ 'game, food' and /misat/ 'deer', with the /s/ < */j/ suggesting previous lexicalization. I'm not sure this is the case, and I don't have good arguments either way right now; but I think it's worth keeping in mind the possibility that /misat/ may be, or not be, the right cognate here. --SM
